  abstract = {{$<$}p{$><$}strong class="journal-contentHeaderColor"{$>$}Abstract.{$<$}/strong{$>$} Nitrogen oxides ({$<$}math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M2" display="inline" overflow="scroll" dspmath="mathml"{$><$}mrow class="chem"{$><$}msub{$><$}mi mathvariant="normal"{$>$}NO{$<$}/mi{$><$}mi{$>$}x{$<$}/mi{$><$}/msub{$><$}mo{$>\equiv<$}/mo{$><$}mi mathvariant="normal"{$>$}NO{$<$}/mi{$><$}mo{$>$}+{$<$}/mo{$><$}msub{$><$}mi mathvariant="normal"{$>$}NO{$<$}/mi{$><$}mn mathvariant="normal"{$>$}2{$<$}/mn{$><$}/msub{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/math{$>$}{$<$}svg:svg xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="85pt" height="13pt" class="svg-formula" dspmath="mathimg" md5hash="f610f94fb6c20199e6f641866e657b1f"{$><$}svg:image xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="acp-18-17017-2018-ie00001.svg" width="85pt" height="13pt" src="acp-18-17017-2018-ie00001.png"/{$><$}/svg:svg{$>$}) in the upper troposphere (UT) have a large impact on global tropospheric ozone and OH (the main atmospheric oxidant). New cloud-sliced observations of UT NO\textsubscript{2} at 450\textendash 280\&thinsp;hPa ({$\sim$}6\textendash 9\&thinsp;km) from the Ozone Monitoring Instrument (OMI) produced by NASA and the Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute (KNMI) provide global coverage to test our understanding of the factors controlling UT NO\textsubscript{\emph{x}}. We find that these products offer useful information when averaged over coarse scales ({$<$}math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M6" display="inline" overflow="scroll" dspmath="mathml"{$><$}mrow{$><$}mn mathvariant="normal"{$>$}20{$<$}/mn{$><$}msup{$><$}mi/{$><$}mo{$>\circ<$}/mo{$><$}/msup{$><$}mo{$>\times <$}/mo{$><$}mn mathvariant="normal"{$>$}32{$<$}/mn{$><$}msup{$><$}mi/{$><$}mo{$>\circ<$}/mo{$><$}/msup{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/math{$>$}{$<$}svg:svg xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="46pt" height="11pt" class="svg-formula" dspmath="mathimg" md5hash="55f159cafb79d8ecf49805e6c5c5fba2"{$><$}svg:im