 PE is 32{$\pm$}15\&thinsp;mol\&thinsp;NO\textsubscript{2} per flash and 6{$\pm$}3\&thinsp;mol\&thinsp;NO\textsubscript{2} per stroke while LNO\textsubscript{\emph{x}} PE is 90{$\pm$}50\&thinsp;mol\&thinsp;NO\textsubscript{\emph{x}} per flash and 17{$\pm$}10\&thinsp;mol\&thinsp;NO\textsubscript{\emph{x}} per stroke. Results reveal that our method reduces the sensitivity to the background NO\textsubscript{2} and includes much of the below-cloud LNO\textsubscript{2}. As the LNO\textsubscript{\emph{x}} parameterization varies in studies, the sensitivity of our calculations to the setting of the amount of lightning NO (LNO) is evaluated. Careful consideration of the ratio of LNO\textsubscript{2} to NO\textsubscript{2} is also needed, given its large influence on the estimation of LNO\textsubscript{2} PE.{$<$}/p{$>$}},
